@NODE install "Installation"
@{u}Installation@{uu}

   Simply copy the entire KingQuest directory to Doors: or unarchive the
KingQuest archive to @{b}Doors:@{ub} and you have it now installed :).

To get it on to the BBS, you can run it from either a login door file or the
actual BBS:

 Key:  Function:   Extra:   Lo acc:  Hi acc:  Filename/Name/Dest/Path:
 
 Q     34          0        0        10000    Doors:KingQuest/KingQuest [path]
 
..or from the login (@{b}Doors:Introdoor.text@{ub}) example:
KingQuest/KingQuest [path]

The [path] is where you want all the completed questionnaires to be put and
where the config and data files should be read from. This is optional, the
default is @{b}Doors:KingQuest/@{ub}. The ability to choose a different path
allows you to store mutiple configs and questionnaire files so that you may
have different questionnaires and stuff.

@{u}Configuration files@{uu}

   Grab a TEXT editor (ED will do), and decide what directory you want all your
files to go and come from for this questionnaire, if you use the default path
then this will be @{b}Doors:KingQuest/KingQuest.cfg@{ub} - @{b}KingQuest.cfg@{ub} is the file
that is read for the config stuff...

@{b}Time to create the questionnaire!@{ub}

On the very first line, there is a number (from 1 to 4), this tells KingQuest
what it should do if a user has already completed the questionnaire..:

1 - SKIPs the questionnaire (displays text and waits for a key press...)
2 - ASKs the user if they to complete it again.
3 - FORCEs the user to complete it again <g>!
4 - SKIPs it, but doesn't wait for a keypress (or display 'already done')

   Once thats over - here comes the big bit ;).. Now, each question you want to
put to the user takes up three lines, the first being the actual question, the
second the length the user can enter for the answer and the third the amount of
lines for this answer, e.g..

What is your hobby?              - The question.
50                               - Maximum length the users answer can be.
1                                - Amount of lines.

@{i}Hotkey answers @{ui}

If you put the length of the answer as 1, it will use a 'hotkey' which means
you user won't have to press enter e.g:

Are you a human being?           - Important question.
1                                - 1 character answer (hotkey).
1                                - 1 line (though you can have more!).

   You can have up to 72 characters for the length of answer and around 999999
lines for it. The question must fit onto a single line though and be no more
than around 70 characters itself.

@{i}New: Pre-set hotkey answers @{ui}

This is a neat little feature as of 4.1, there are currently 3 you can use.
It works just like hotkeys in which the user doesn't have to press return, but
the user's answer is limited to 2 keys (pre-set in KingQuest). The first is a
Yes/No type answer, the user can only press Y or N as an answer - anything else
won't be accepted, and Yes or No is written to the answers file, the second is
Male/Female, M or F, which works in the same way. Third there is Agree/Disagree
or Accept/Decline, it's A or D, so it can be used depending on the wording,
although in the answer file it will appear as Agree or Disagree.

You can use these by setting the question length to -1 for Yes/No, -2 for
Male/Female, or -3 for Agree/Disagree. You may use multiple line answers,
but you'll probably always set this to 1 (for obvious reasons!). e.g.

Do you believe in Aliens?        - UFO BBS important question :)
-1                               - Yes/No answer accepted only.
1                                - 1 line (though you can have more!).

@{u}Adding An Introductory Message@{uu}

   If you want a small message explaining what the questionnaire is about, all
you need to do is make a text or ANSI file (without screen clears or cursor
positioning) with the text you want to say and save it to the directory with
that questionnaire's stuff in called @{b}Message.text@{ub}, simple huh?

   Now you have it all installed, go and check out the @{" in use " LINK use}
section and have a good old read of the rest of the guide too ;). 

@{u}Adding a Bye Message@{uu}

   KingQuest internally writes "Thanks for completeing this questionnaire!"
after the user has completed the questionnaire, if you don't want this to come
up then you can write your own text in a text or ANSI editor (without screen
clears or cursor positioning) and save it to the directory with the rest of
the questionnaire stuff called @{b}Bye.Text@{ub} - it's that simple :). Have
a play to see what looks best for you!

   Now you have it all installed, go and check out the @{" in use " LINK use}
section and have a good old read of the rest of the guide too ;). 

@ENDNODE


@NODE use "In use"
@{u}In use@{uu}

   Once you have @{" installed " LINK install} the door, it's time to check it out,
when you first run it you will be presented by an introductory message and the
@{"Message.text" LINK install 99} (if you put one in), if you have already run it then something
will happen depending on what MODE you set in the @{" configuration " LINK install 22}.

   Now the questions will start, you can skip answers (or prematurely end
mutiple line answers) by leaving it blank, this will be filled in by
"<< Skipped Answer >>" in the questionnaire (unless its a multple lined answer
in which case it will only say that if they didn't enter anything on the first
line). If the carrier is lost while filling out, it will save the questionnaire
but with ** LOST CARRIER ** in it, and it won't say they completed the
questionnaire - cos they didn't. Once it gets to the end, it will thank them
for their time or display your @{"Bye.text" LINK install 99} and then quit. That's it.

   The file it creates is @{b}USERNAME.quest@{ub}, you can view this with any normal
text viewer (contains questions & answers), you may delete this file as the
users that have already accessed the questionnaire are stored in a file called
@{b}User.dat@{ub}. If you delete @{b}User.dat@{ub} it will restart the questionnaire.

@ENDNODE


